chapter.para:
    The general calling scheme for the other languages supported
    by PLplot is as follows, using the function
    &plline; as an example.




	  C: plline( n, x, y );





	  Ada/standard: Draw_Curve( x, y );





	  Ada/traditional: plline( x, y );





	  C++: pls->line(n, x, y );





	  D: plline( x, y );





	  F95: plline( x, y )





	  Java: pls.line( x, y );





	  Lua: pl.line( x, y )





	  OCaml: plline x y;





	  Octave: plline( x', y' );





	  Perl/PDL: plline( $x, $y );





	  Python: plline( x, y )





	  Tcl/Tk: $w cmd plline x y




    Note that in all our supported languages other than C and C++, the
    argument n (which specifies
    the length of the input vectors
    x and
    y) is not used in the
    argument list since that information is already available from the
    vector (and matrix in the general case) arguments themselves.  This is
    what we refer to above as the redacted argument form of
    the function.

sect1.para:
Returns 8-bit RGB values (0-255) for given color from cmap0 (see
).  Values are
negative if an invalid color id is given.

Set the background color (color 0 in cmap0) by 8-bit RGB value
and PLFLT alpha transparency value (see
).

Shade individual region on the basis of value.  Use &plshades;
    if you want to shade a number of contiguous regions using continuous
    colors.  In particular the edge contours are treated properly in
    &plshades;.  If you attempt to do contiguous regions with &plshade;
    the contours at the edge of the shade are partially obliterated by
    subsequent plots of contiguous shaded regions.
